      <h1 class="text-3xl sm:text-4xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-gray-900">Home Office Cable Management: A Complete Guide to a Clean Desk</h1>
      <p class="mt-4 text-lg leading-8 text-gray-600">
        I ignored cable management for three years. When I finally spent an afternoon fixing it, my desk felt like a completely different workspace. Here is everything I learned.
      </p>

      <div class="mt-10 prose prose-lg prose-gray max-w-none">

        <p>For years my desk looked like a snake pit. Monitor power cable, laptop charger, external hard drive, phone charger, desk lamp, webcam, microphone — all crossing and tangling under and around my desk. I told myself it did not matter because the mess was mostly hidden. But I was wrong. Every time I reached under the desk to plug something in, I had to untangle three cables. Dust collected in the knots. And the visual clutter, even just in my peripheral vision, made my workspace feel chaotic in a way that subtly affected my focus.</p>

        <p>A 2011 study from Princeton University's Neuroscience Institute found that visual clutter competes for your attention and reduces your brain's ability to process information. Your visual cortex does not just ignore mess — it actively processes it, burning cognitive resources that could be going toward your actual work. A clean desk is not just about aesthetics. It is about reclaiming your own attention.</p>

        <p>The good news: cable management is genuinely easy once you know what to buy and where to put things. It took me one Sunday afternoon and about $40 in supplies to go from chaos to clean. Here is the system.</p>

        <h2>Step 1: Audit your cables</h2>

        <p>Before you buy anything, unplug every single cable from your desk setup. Every. Single. One. Lay them all out on the floor and count them. Most desks have between 8 and 15 cables — more than you think. Now remove any cable that belongs to a device you no longer use. That old printer cable, the charger for a phone you replaced two years ago, the USB hub you never actually plugged in. You will probably find at least two orphaned cables. We all do.</p>

        <p>Now group the remaining cables by type: power cables, data cables (USB, HDMI, DisplayPort, Thunderbolt), and audio cables. Each group needs slightly different management because they have different thicknesses, flexibility, and routing requirements.</p>

        <h2>Step 2: Mount the power strip under your desk</h2>

        <p>This is the single most impactful move in cable management and it costs about $15. Instead of the power strip sitting on the floor collecting dust, mount it to the underside of your desk. Everything plugs in right under the desk surface — no cables running down to the floor, no power strip visible, no tripping over cords.</p>

        <p>You have two options: screw-mount the power strip directly into the desk (if it has mounting holes on the back, which most do) or use a clamp-on cable tray that holds the power strip and all the excess cable slack. I use the clamp-on tray approach because it is non-destructive — no drilling into the desk — and it makes it easy to add or remove cables later.</p>

        <p>Products that work: the simple stick-on cable clips that come in packs of 20 for $8, or a metal under-desk cable tray ($15-25 on Amazon) that clamps to the back edge of the desk. The metal tray is better if you have a lot of cables and power bricks; the clips are fine if you have a simpler setup.</p>

        <h2>Step 3: Route cables in layers, not bundles</h2>

        <p>The beginner mistake is to gather all your cables into one giant bundle and zip-tie them together. That looks clean for about a week — until you need to swap out one cable and have to cut all the zip ties. Instead, route cables in layers:</p>

        <p><strong>Layer 1 (power):</strong> All power cables and power bricks go first. They are the thickest and least flexible, so they get priority routing. Run them along the back edge of the desk or inside a cable tray. Plug everything into the mounted power strip.</p>

        <p><strong>Layer 2 (data):</strong> USB, HDMI, DisplayPort, Thunderbolt. These are thinner and more flexible. Route them separately from the power cables — power cables can cause interference with unshielded data cables, though this is rare with modern cables. More importantly, data cables change more often (new monitor, new hub, new device), so keeping them separate makes swaps easy.</p>

        <p><strong>Layer 3 (charging and temporary):</strong> Phone charger, watch charger, the cable for your wireless earbuds. These are the cables you grab and unplug frequently. Route them to a specific spot on your desk — a charging station or a dedicated corner — and use magnetic cable clips or a cable drop to keep them accessible.</p>

        <h2>Step 4: Use the right fasteners for each situation</h2>

        <p>Velcro ties are better than zip ties 95% of the time. They are reusable, adjustable, and do not require scissors or a knife to remove. Buy a roll of velcro cable ties ($8 for 50) and you will never use zip ties again. The only time zip ties make sense is for permanent installations inside walls or raceways — situations where you will literally never need to access that cable again.</p>

        <p>Adhesive cable clips are the unsung heroes of desk cable management. They stick to the underside of your desk or along the back edge and hold individual cables in place. The 3M adhesive on good clips holds for years. Position them every 12-18 inches along the cable path to prevent sagging. Pro tip: wipe the mounting surface with rubbing alcohol before sticking — it removes dust and skin oils that prevent adhesion.</p>

        <p>Cable sleeves (the spiral-wrap or split-loom kind) are useful for groups of cables that run the same path — like everything going from your desk down to the floor. They turn five visible cables into one clean line. Just do not sleeve cables you might need to separate — un-sleeving is annoying.</p>

        <h2>Step 5: Handle the visible parts</h2>

        <p>The cables that run from the back of your desk to your monitor and peripherals are the ones you actually see. For these, a cable raceway or a desk grommet makes a big difference. A raceway is a plastic channel that mounts to the wall or the back of the desk; cables run inside it and exit at specific points. A desk grommet is a circular insert that fits into a hole in your desk surface — cables drop through it and disappear underneath.</p>

        <p>If your desk does not have a built-in grommet hole, you can clamp a cable management channel to the back edge instead. The IKEA Signum rack ($15) is the classic budget option — it is a simple metal rack that screws into the underside of your desk and holds cables and power strips. It is not pretty, but it is under the desk, so no one sees it.</p>

        <p>For the cables that run from your desk to the wall (ethernet, power strip to outlet, etc.), a floor cable cover is essential. These are rubber or plastic channels that lie flat on the floor and protect cables from being stepped on. They cost about $15 and prevent both tripping hazards and cable damage.</p>

        <h2>Step 6: Label both ends of every cable</h2>

        <p>This sounds obsessive. It is obsessive. But six months from now, when you need to unplug one specific thing and cannot tell which identical black cable goes where, you will be glad you spent the two minutes to label them. Masking tape and a Sharpie work fine. Or get a $10 label maker and feel unreasonably satisfied every time you look under your desk.</p>

        <p>Label both ends. "Monitor USB-C" on the monitor end and "Monitor USB-C → Laptop" on the laptop end. When you move or reconfigure, you will not have to trace cables by hand.</p>

        <h2>The shopping list</h2>

        <ul>
          <li>Under-desk cable tray ($15-25)</li>
          <li>Velcro cable ties, 50-pack ($8)</li>
          <li>Adhesive cable clips, 20-pack ($8)</li>
          <li>Cable sleeve / split loom, 10ft ($10)</li>
          <li>Floor cable cover, if needed ($15)</li>
          <li>Masking tape + Sharpie ($3, you already own these)</li>
          <li><strong>Total: $44-69</strong></li>
        </ul>

        <p>One afternoon. Less than $70. And your desk goes from chaos to clean in a way that makes every workday feel just a little bit better. That is a pretty good return on investment.</p>
